<DOC><DOCNO> AP890913-0226 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2200EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Storms     09-13 0227</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Brazil-Storms,0234</SECOND><HEAD>12 Dead, 1000s Homeless in Brazilian Storms</HEAD><DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three days of pounding rain andhigh winds left 12 people dead and drove thousands from their homesin southern Brazil, civil defense officials said Wednesday.   Three people drowned and a fourth was killed by lightning inCuritiba, capital of Parana state, 500 miles southwest of Rio,Carlos Daher of the civil defense said in a telephone interview.Among the dead was a 16-year-old boy, swept away by a flooded riverin the slum neighborhood of Vila Sofia.   ``The river rose so high that parts of the city looked like alake,'' Daher said of the flooding. ``But the rain has stopped now,and people who were driven from their homes are going back to cleanup.''   Six people died in western Parana when winds of up to 65 mphknocked down buildings and blew off roofs, leaving 4,000 homeless,Daher said.   Worst hit was rural Pato Branco, where winds destroyed the homesof 2,500 people, he said.   The homeless were being sheltered in churches, schools and publicbuildings, Daher said.   In Santa Catarina state, heavy rains caused a gold mine in thecity of Lages to collapse Tuesday, trapping and killing two men,officials said.   Heavy rain also left 2,000 people homeless in Rio Grande do Sul,Brazil's southernmost state.</TEXT></DOC>